    title FCC AMP Timestamp Microservice
  body
    div(class="container")
    h1 FCC AMP Timestamp Microservice
      h2 User Stories
      ol(class="user-stories")
        li The API endpoint is #[code GET project_url/api/:date_string?]
        li A date string is valid if can be successfully parsed by #[code new Date(date_string)].  Note that the unix timestamp needs to be an #[strong integer] (not a string) specifying #[strong milliseconds].  In our test we will use date strings compliant with ISO-8601 (e.g. #[code "2016-11-20"]) because this will ensure an UTC timestamp.
        li If the date string is #[strong empty] it should be equivalent to trigger #[code new Date()], i.e. the service uses the current timestamp.
        li If the date string is #[strong valid] the api returns a JSON having the structure #[code {"unix": date.getTime(), "utc": date.toUTCString()}] e.g. #[code {"unix": 1479663089000 ,"utc": "Sun, 20 Nov 2016 17:31:29 GMT"}]
        li If the date string is #[strong invalid] the api returns a JSON having the structure #[code {"error" : "Invalid Date" }].

h2 Example Usage
ul
li
  a(href="api/2015-12-25") [project url]/api/2015-12-25
li
  a(href="api/1451001600000") [project url]/api/1451001600000

h2 Example Output
ul
li #[code {"unix": 1451001600000, "utc": "Fri, 25 Dec 2015 00:00:00 GMT"}]
